'''Fallbacks''', or fallback [[Special:MyLanguage/Avatars|avatars]], are optimized avatars that serve as a placeholder<ref>[https://medium.com/vrchat/vrchat-on-quest-avatar-performance-woes-1a3cc228a442 "VRChat on Quest: Avatar Performance Woes"] on ''[https://medium.com/vrchat Medium]''. Dated March 18, 2021. Retrieved September 16, 2021.</ref> for when the user can't see another user's original avatar, such as when users are on different [[Special:MyLanguage/Platforms|platforms]]. Fallbacks were introduced to VRChat, with the 2021.1.5<ref>[https://docs.vrchat.com/docs/vrchat-202115 "VRChat 2021.1.5"] on ''[[docs.vrchat.com]]''. Dated March 23, 2021. Retrieved September 16, 2025.</ref> update, on March 23, 2021.

==Avatar Fallback System==
[[File:Fallback system.webp|thumb|A VRChat graphic from 2021, describing the ability to select a Fallback avatar, to show users on Quest.]]
The Avatar Fallback System ''(not to be confused with the [https://creators.vrchat.com/avatars/shader-fallback-system Shader Blocking and Fallback System])'' is a way for users to select which fallback avatar is shown to others when they aren't able to see a user's original avatar. It is also indicated as an icon on the nameplate, letting users know that they're viewing a fallback and why.

===Identifying fallbacks===
Fallbacks can be identified when viewing another user's fallback by viewing their nameplate. Fallbacks are indicated with a blue feather icon.

==== Fallback types ====
In the bottom right corner of the blue feather icon, along with another icon explaining why the fallback avatar is being displayed instead. Here's what these icons mean:
